@realmoney Full of Sound and Fury Signifying Nothing? * Apparently bullish reversals matter (Wednesday) * But bearish reversals don't matter (Thursday and Friday) "Out, out, brief candle. Life is nothing more than an illusion. It’s like a poor actor who struts and worries for

his hour on the stage and then is never heard from again. Life is a story told by an idiot, full of noise and emotional disturbance but devoid of meaning." - William Shakespeare, Macbeth (Act 5, Scene 5) Yesterday in Hyberbolic Investment Commentary realmoney.thestreet.com/doug… I

made the following observations: "A lot of commentators are making too much about yesterday's rally off of the lows to breakeven (at the low the S&P was about -27 points) and today's relatively small eight-handle rally in the S&P Index. Given the role of passive products and

strategies in exaggerating short-term market moves -- a net change in the S&P of five or six handles over the last 1 1/2 trading days means absolutely nothing even though many want you to think it is meaningful. The sort of hyperbolic commentary tells you more about

the prognosticators than their prognostications." Today the market has again reversed lower and is now about 20 S&P handles below the day's highs. The proximate cause for the reversal is that the Chinese trade delegation is leaving the US earlier than expected.
